definition.value: A dicarboximide that is 4-(2-hydroxyethyl)piperidine-2,6-dione in which one of the hydrogens attached to the carbon  bearing the hydroxy group is replaced by a 3,5-dimethyl-2-oxocyclohexyl group. It is an antibiotic produced by the bacterium Streptomyces griseus.

A pyranoindolizinoquinoline that is pyrano[3',4':6,7]indolizino[1,2-b]quinoline which is substituted by oxo groups at positions 3 and 14, and by an ethyl group and a hydroxy group at position 4 (the S enantiomer).
Any aldehyde having an oxo substituent at the 2-position.
A heteroglycan consisting of a mannan backbone with galactose side groups.
The D-enantiomer of isoleucine.
A trimethylxanthine in which the three methyl groups are located at positions 1, 3, and 7. A purine alkaloid that occurs naturally in tea and coffee.
A surfactant (or a mixture containing one or more surfactants) having cleaning properties in dilute solutions.
A member of the class of benzimidazoles that is benzimidazole in which the hydrogen at position 2 is replaced by an amino group.
The sodium salt of hydrogen azide (hydrazoic acid).
Acetaldehyde substituted at C-2 by chlorine.
An alpha-amino acid that is alanine bearing an indol-3-yl substituent at position 3.

A diamminedichloroplatinum compound in which the two ammine ligands and two chloro ligands are oriented in a cis planar configuration around the central platinum ion. An anticancer drug that interacts with, and forms cross-links between, DNA and proteins, it is used as a neoplasm inhibitor to treat solid tumours, primarily of the testis and ovary. Commonly but incorrectly described as an alkylating agent due to its mechanism of action (but it lacks alkyl groups).
A broad-spectrum polyketide antibiotic produced by the Streptomyces genus of actinobacteria.
An optically active form of histidine having D-configuration.
An amino cyclitol consisting of scyllo-inositol with the hydroxy groups at positions 1 and 3 replaced by unsubstituted amino groups.
An aromatic amino acid that is alanine in which one of the methyl hydrogens is substituted by a phenyl group.
A glycosylglucose formed by an alpha-(1->6)-linkage between D-galactose and D-glucose.
A chromium group element atom that has atomic number 24.
A bornane monoterpenoid that is 1,7,7-trimethylbicyclo[2.2.1]heptane substituted by a hydroxy group at position 2.
An alpha-D-glucan in which the glucose units are connected by (1->3) linkages.
An optically active form of asparagine having D-configuration.
A complex between iron(III) and three hydroxamic acid groups, used for iron transport.

A member of the class of rotenones that consists of 1,2,12,12a-tetrahydrochromeno[3,4-b]furo[2,3-h]chromen-6(6aH)-one substituted at position 2 by a prop-1-en-2-yl group and at positions 8 and 9 by methoxy groups (the 2R,6aS,12aS-isomer). A non-systemic insecticide, it is the principal insecticidal constituent of derris (the dried rhizome and root of Derris elliptica).
The D-enantiomer of leucine.
An aldohexose that is the C-4 epimer of glucose.
A 2-carbon sulfoxide in which the sulfur atom has two methyl substituents.
An alpha-amino acid that consists of butyric acid bearing an amino substituent at position 2 and a carbamoyl substituent at position 4.

Any member of a group of fat-soluble 2-methyl-1,4-napthoquinones that exhibit biological activity against vitamin K deficiency. Vitamin K is required for the synthesis of prothrombin and certain other blood coagulation factors.
An optically active form of tyrosine having D-configuration.
A phosphatidylglycerol composed of two molecules of phosphatidic acid covalently linked to a molecule of glycerol.

A 1-ribosylimidazolecarboxamide in which the carboxamide group is situated at position 4 of the imidazole ring, which is further substituted at position 5 by an amino group. A purine nucleoside analogue and activator of AMP-activated protein kinase, it is  is used for the treatment of acute lymphoblastic leukemia and is reported to have cardioprotective effects.
A twelve-membered cyclodepsipeptide composed of three repeating D-alpha-hydroxyisovaleryl-D-valyl-L-lactoyl-L-valyl units joined in sequence. An antibiotic found in several Streptomyces strains.
A L-glutamyl ester that is the  alpha-methyl ester derivative of L-glutamic acid.
A (9Z)-12-hydroxyoctadec-9-enoic acid in which the 12-hydroxy group has R-configuration..
A cinchona alkaloid consisting of cinchonine with the hydrogen at the 6-position of the quinoline ring substituted by methoxy.
A one-carbon compound that is ammonia in which one of the hydrogens is replaced by a carboxy group. Although carbamic acid derivatives are common, carbamic acid itself has never been synthesised.
A metal fluoride salt with a Na(+) counterion.
A ketohexose that is an isomer of glucose.
Any member of the phosphoinositide family of compounds, of which seven occur naturally.
A monoterpene that is toluene substituted by an isopropyl group at position 4.
